Microbiome Feature Analysis

LaShanda Williams, PhD

December 6, 2025

Research Summary

This analysis applies compositional dataaware statistical methods to identify key bacterial features differentiating clinical vaginal conditions, using both community-wide and taxon-specific approaches. Raw OTU count data were log-centered (CLR) transformed to mitigate compositional bias, and alpha diversity indices were computed to assess ecological structure. Multivariate differences between clinical groups (BV, BVVC, and Healthy) were tested using PERMANOVA, while dispersion differences were evaluated via BETADISPER to ensure that observed separations reflect true centroid shifts rather than increased variability.

Univariate statistical tests (Dunn and Wilcoxon) were conducted on CLR-transformed bacterial features to detect pairwise differences in taxon-level abundance. Multiple hypothesis correction was applied, revealing strong and consistent shifts in bacterial features between BV and both other clinical groups, while BVVC samples remained statistically similar to Healthy controls. Together, these analyses establish BV as the dominant bacterial dysbiosis condition and demonstrate that VVC lacks a robust bacterial signature, forming a biologically grounded foundation for subsequent machine learning classification and SHAP-based interpretability.

min_prevalence <- 5

1.3 Centered Log-Ratio (CLR) Transformation

condition_vector <- metadata_aligned[colnames(otu_counts_final), "Status_Code"]

clr_results <- aldex.clr(
    reads = otu_counts_final,
    conds = as.character(condition_vector),
    mc.samples = 128,      # proper MC sampling
    denom = "all",
    verbose = FALSE,
    useMC = TRUE           # <- FORCE Monte Carlo sampling
)
## conditions vector supplied
## multicore environment is is OK -- using the BiocParallel package
## computing center with all features
clr_mc <- slot(clr_results, "analysisData")

if (length(clr_mc) < 1) stop("ALDEx2 returned zero CLR Monte Carlo samples.")

num_samples <- length(clr_mc)
num_features <- nrow(clr_mc[[1]])  # number of features
clr_feature_matrix <- matrix(NA, nrow = num_samples, ncol = num_features)

sample_ids <- names(clr_mc)
rownames(clr_feature_matrix) <- sample_ids

for (i in seq_along(clr_mc)) {
  clr_feature_matrix[i, ] <- rowMeans(clr_mc[[i]])
}

colnames(clr_feature_matrix) <- paste0("CLR_", rownames(clr_mc[[1]]))
clr_feature_matrix <- as.data.frame(clr_feature_matrix)

1.4 Alpha Diversity Calculation

otu_samples_in_rows <- as.data.frame(t(otu_counts_final))

alpha_diversity <- data.frame(
    SampleID = rownames(otu_samples_in_rows),
    Shannon_Index = diversity(otu_samples_in_rows, index = "shannon"),
    Observed_Richness = specnumber(otu_samples_in_rows)
)

rownames(alpha_diversity) <- alpha_diversity$SampleID
alpha_diversity$SampleID <- NULL

1.5 Dataset Finalization

metadata_to_join <- metadata_aligned %>%

2. Multivariate Feature Validation

2.1 Global Separation (PERMANOVA & BETADISPER)

PERMANOVA using CLR-transformed Aitchison distances demonstrated highly significant differences in microbiome composition between clinical groups. - Microbial community structure differed significantly between at least two clinical groups (p = 0.001).
- ~13.5% of variation in global microbiome composition is explained by clinical classification (R = 0.1348).

A BETADISPER test was performed to ensure that PERMANOVA differences reflect true centroid separation and are not artifacts of differing dispersion. - There is no significant difference in dispersion between groups (p = 0.073).
- Therefore, the significant PERMANOVA findings reflect true compositional shifts, not variation in spread.

df_full <- df_full_features_with_status

Pairwise PERMANOVA comparisons reveal BV drives strong restructuring of the vaginal microbiome, while BVVC and Healthy samples are much closer in microbial composition.

# --- 2. Pairwise PERMANOVA (Multivariate Post-Hoc) ---
# Calculate the distance matrix on CLR features
dist_matrix <- dist(df_full[, clr_cols], method = "euclidean")
groups <- df_full$Status_Code

pairwise_permanova_results <- data.frame()
group_levels <- levels(factor(groups))

for (i in 1:(length(group_levels) - 1)) {
    for (j in (i + 1):length(group_levels)) {
        group1 <- group_levels[i]
        group2 <- group_levels[j]

        # Subset data for the pair
        subset_samples <- df_full %>% filter(Status_Code %in% c(group1, group2))
        subset_dist <- dist(subset_samples[, clr_cols], method = "euclidean")

        # Run PERMANOVA on the subset
        res <- adonis2(subset_dist ~ Status_Code, data = subset_samples, permutations = 999)

        # Store results
        pairwise_permanova_results <- rbind(pairwise_permanova_results, data.frame(
            Comparison = paste(group1, "vs", group2),
            R2 = res$R2[1],
            P_Value = res$`Pr(>F)`[1]
        ))
    }
}

# Apply FDR correction (Benjamini-Hochberg)
pairwise_permanova_results <- pairwise_permanova_results %>%
    mutate(FDR_P_Value = p.adjust(P_Value, method = "fdr"))

print(pairwise_permanova_results)

3. Univariate Biomarker Validation

3.1 Post-Hoc Dunns Test

Post-hoc Dunns tests were applied to CLR-transformed bacterial abundance features to quantify pairwise differences between clinical conditions (BV, BVVC, and Healthy controls). Results were adjusted for multiple comparisons using the BenjaminiHochberg method.

  1. BV was significantly different from both Healthy and BVVC across nearly all top discriminative features.

    • For the five strongest features (CLR_1, CLR_14, CLR_17, CLR_3, CLR_43), p.adj ranged from 10 to 10 for BV vs Healthy, and from 10 to 10 for BV vs BVVC. These results confirm that BV consistently produces large, biologically meaningful shifts in multiple taxa.

  2. BVVC and Healthy groups showed no significant differences for all but one feature.

    • Across CLR_1, CLR_17, CLR_3, and CLR_43, BCONT vs BVVC comparisons were non-significant.
    • The only exception was CLR_14, which showed a modest but significant difference (p.adj = 0.0017). This indicates that BVVC does not produce systematic bacterial alterations, further distinguishing it from BV.

  3. Effect direction was consistent across features:

    • BV samples had significantly lower CLR values for stability-associated commensals (CLR_1, CLR_3, CLR_17, CLR_43),
    • while BV samples showed elevated CLR_14, consistent with BV-associated anaerobic enrichment.

The Dunns test results reinforce the PERMANOVA findings by revealing:

  • Strong and widespread univariate abundance shifts in BV,
  • Minimal bacterial disruption in BVVC,
  • and stable commensal profiles in healthy controls.

Overall, the Dunns test conclusions support a mechanistic model where BV reflects ecological collapse and opportunistic dysbiosis, while VVC is not driven by bacterial restructuring.

dunn_test_results <- df_full %>%
    select(Status_Code, all_of(top_biomarkers)) %>%
    pivot_longer(-Status_Code, names_to = "Feature", values_to = "Value") %>%
    group_by(Feature) %>%
    # Performs Dunn's test for all pairs of groups, automatically applying FDR correction
    dunn_test(Value ~ Status_Code, p.adjust.method = "fdr")

print(dunn_test_results)

3.2 Visualization of Biomarker Distributions

plot_clr_features <- function(data, feature_name, dunn_results) {
  
  dunn_feature <- dunn_results %>%
    filter(Feature == feature_name) %>%
    arrange(p.adj) %>%
    mutate(
      y.position = max(data[[feature_name]], na.rm = TRUE) + 0.2 * row_number()
    )
  
  p <- ggplot(data, aes(x = Status_Code, y = !!sym(feature_name), fill = Status_Code)) +
    geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.7) +
    geom_jitter(width = 0.2, size = 1.5, alpha = 0.6) +
    labs(
      title = paste("CLR Abundance of", feature_name, "by Clinical Status"),
      x = "Clinical Status",
      y = feature_name
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    stat_pvalue_manual(
      dunn_feature,
      hide.ns = TRUE,
      label = "p.adj.signif"
    )
  
  return(p)
}

3.2 Pairwise Mann-Whitney U (Wilcoxon Rank-Sum) Tests (FDR Corrected)

Pairwise Wilcoxon Rank-Sum tests were used to assess univariate differences in CLR-transformed bacterial abundances between the three diagnostic categories (BV, BVVC, and Healthy), with BenjaminiHochberg correction applied to maintain false discovery control across multiple comparisons.

  1. BV vs Healthy (BCONT)

    • The majority of CLR features were extremely significantly different between BV and BCONT, with FDR-adjusted p-values typically 10.
    • These results demonstrate a strong taxon-level effect of BV dysbiosis, consistent with loss of commensal stability and enrichment of opportunistic organisms.

  2. BV vs BVVC

    • Nearly all features also showed highly significant differences between BV and BVVC, with FDR-adjusted p-values 10 for the top discriminating CLR variables.
    • This supports a clear separation of BV from BVVC, mirroring PERMANOVA and Dunn test results, and confirming the biological distinctness of BV.

  3. Healthy (BCONT) vs BVVC

    • For almost all features, no significant differences were found between BCONT and BVVC after FDR correction.
    • The only exception was CLR_14, where a moderate but statistically significant difference persisted (FDR p.adj = 0.0017).
    • These results confirm that BVVC closely resembles Healthy microbial structure, with no strong taxon-level perturbation.

The Wilcoxon-based findings provide strong corroboration of the ecological conclusions drawn from multivariate PERMANOVA and post-hoc Dunn testing:

  • BV induces widespread disruption of bacterial abundance, affecting many microbes simultaneously.
  • BVVC produces weak, inconsistent bacterial alterations, resulting in a community profile statistically similar to Healthy controls.
  • Taxon-level dysbiosis signatures reflect ecosystem collapse rather than invasion by a single pathogen.

These outcomes strengthen the interpretation that machine learning models captured true biological structure, not statistical artifacts, and justify the difficulty of distinguishing BVVC from Healthy based solely on bacterial features.

wilcox_results <- df_full %>%
    select(Status_Code, all_of(top_biomarkers)) %>%
    pivot_longer(-Status_Code, names_to = "Feature", values_to = "Value") %>%
    group_by(Feature) %>%
    # Performs Wilcoxon test for all pairs of groups, automatically applying FDR correction
    wilcox_test(Value ~ Status_Code, p.adjust.method = "fdr")

Conclusion

Taken together, the results of the PERMANOVA, BETADISPER, Dunns post-hoc testing, and Wilcoxon pairwise comparisons demonstrate that bacterial vaginosis (BV) is associated with a strong and widespread restructuring of the vaginal microbiome, whereas vulvovaginal candidiasis (VVC) shows minimal and inconsistent bacterial shifts and remains statistically similar to healthy controls. This pattern held across both multivariate and univariate analytical frameworks, indicating that BV produces true compositional displacement rather than artifacts of dispersion, and affects many taxa simultaneously rather than a single dominant pathogen. In contrast, VVC lacks a bacterial dysbiosis signature, consistent with its well-established fungal etiology.

These findings establish a biologically interpretable foundation for predictive modeling. Because BV induces a large and coherent signal in both community structure and taxon-level abundances, we expect supervised machine learning approaches to perform well at discriminating BV from non-BV samples. In contrast, the absence of strong bacterial alterations in VVC suggests reduced separability and lower classification performance for this group, reflecting both biological heterogeneity and weaker microbial diagnostic signal.

Next, we apply machine learning classifiers to these CLR-transformed features and assess their predictive behavior, interpretability, and concordance with the statistical patterns established here.
